Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1385–1422":"1385–1422","1380–1442":"1380–1442","1405–1479":"1405–1479","1408–Female":"1408–Deceased","1430–1470":"1430–1470","1432–Male":"1432–Deceased","1434–Male":"1434–Deceased","1436–Female":"1436–Deceased","1385":"1385","1470":"1470","1380":"1380","before 1405":"before 1405","about 1408":"about 1408","1436":"1436","1479":"1479","1434":"1434","1422":"1422","about 1405":"about 1405","1432":"1432","1442":"1442","1430":"1430","1408":"1408","1405":"1405","Clifton, Cheshire, England":"Clifton, Cheshire, England","of Dukenfield, Cheshire, England":"Dukinfield, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England","Dukinfield, Cheshire, England":"Dukinfield, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Brereton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places called Brereton, in Cheshire and Staffordshire, and sometimes from Brearton in Yorkshire or Brierton in Durham. Brereton in Staffordshire is named with Old English <i>brǣr</i>, <i>brēr</i> ‘briar’ + Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ as its final element; the others are named with Old English <i>brǣr</i>, <i>brēr</i> ‘briar’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brewerton","meanings":["English: variant of   Brereton  , the result of confusion by folk etymology with the occupational name   Brewer  ."]},{"name":"Brierton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Brierton in County Durham (formerly in Yorkshire) or Brearton in North Yorkshire, which are both named with Old English <i>brēr</i> ‘briar’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead’, or Brereton in Cheshire, which has the same origin (see   Brereton  )."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen Brereton was born in 1385, in Runcorn, Cheshire, England. She married Robert Dukinfield before 1405, in Dukinfield, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 3 daughters. She died in 1422, in Clifton, Cheshire, England, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1385–1422":"1385–1422","1380–1442":"1380–1442","1405–1479":"1405–1479","1408–Female":"1408–Surnud","1430–1470":"1430–1470","1432–Male":"1432–Surnud","1434–Male":"1434–Surnud","1436–Female":"1436–Surnud","1385":"1385","1470":"1470","1380":"1380","before 1405":"enne 1405","about 1408":"umbes 1408","1436":"1436","1479":"1479","1434":"1434","1422":"1422","about 1405":"umbes 1405","1432":"1432","1442":"1442","1430":"1430","1408":"1408","1405":"1405","Clifton, Cheshire, England":"Clifton, Cheshire, England","of Dukenfield, Cheshire, England":"Dukinfield, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England","Dukinfield, Cheshire, England":"Dukinfield, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1385–1422":"1385–1422","1380–1442":"1380–1442","1405–1479":"1405–1479","1408–Female":"1408–Kuollut","1430–1470":"1430–1470","1432–Male":"1432–Kuollut","1434–Male":